Ancient history as a term refers to the aggregate of past events from the beginning of writing and recorded human history and extending as far as the post-classical history. The phrase may be used either to refer to the period of time or the academic discipline. The span of recorded history is roughly 5,000 years, beginning with Sumerian Cuneiform script; the oldest discovered form of coherent writing from the protoliterate period around the 30th century BCE. Ancient History covers all continents inhabited by humans in the 3,000 BCE – 500 CE period.

Cultural history combines the approaches of anthropology and history to look at popular cultural traditions and cultural interpretations of historical experience. It examines the records and narrative descriptions of past matter, encompassing the continuum of events (occurring in succession and leading from the past to the present and even into the future) pertaining to a culture.
The history of the developing, use, and availability of clothing, as well as fashion and cultural contexts of clothing.
The history of cross-dressing in which a person wears clothes of a gender expression that one does not identify with.
Gender history is a sub-field of history and gender studies, which looks at the past from the perspective of gender.

The study of the role that women have played in history and the methods required to do so. It includes the study of the history of the growth of woman's rights throughout recorded history, personal achievement over a period of time, the examination of individual and groups of women of historical significance, and the effect that historical events have had on women.
The study of the role that men have played in history.

A branch of social history which studies instances of lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender behavior and peoples throughout different cultures in ancient history, with special regard to the persecution of such people.
